properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibilities under snow and in blowing snow are expected on Wednesday. A coastal low pressure system is moving toward the Gulf of St Lawrence. Snowfall amounts between 10 and 15 centimetres with easterly winds to 70 km/h are expected over the Lower North Shore. These conditions will give blowing snow for several hours during the day. ### Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong winter storm is bringing heavy snow to the Coquihalla Highway - Hope to Merritt. Snow continues this morning above 900 metres along the highway. The snow level will rise later this morning to near the summit at which point the snow will become heavy and wet. The wet snow will change to rain this evening as the snow level rises above the summit. The highest snowfall will be near the summit with total accumulation of 10 to 20 cm by this evening. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 20 to 30 cm is expected. A strong winter storm continues to hammer the Kootenays with snow today. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 20 to 30 cm is expected. A strong winter storm continues to hammer the Kootenays with snow today. Over Arrow-Slocan, as well as northern portions of Kootenay Lake 15 to 25 cm is expected by Wednesday morning. For the West Kootenay region, the highest accumulations are expected over higher terrain and will amount to 20 to 30 cm storm total. In the Elk Valley region, areas near Fernie and Morrissey can expect upwards of 15 to 25 cm of snow this afternoon through to early Wednesday morning. Total snowfall accumulation over Kootenay Pass is expected to be 20 to 40 cm. The heavy snow is expected to ease by Wednesday morning. ### Poor weather conditions may contribute to transportation delays. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca.
